Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

records.addlTxt: Defendant's Motion to Extend Time Limits

2:00 PM Defendant Alaquay D Templeton in court.  Attorney Michael Hughes in court for Alaquay D Templeton.  Prosecuting attorney Alexander Paul Seifert in court for the State of Wisconsin. Called 22CF108 which is set for PH. State calls Sgt. Luther Kelley. Hughes requests sequestration of witness. Court grants request. Witness sworn in, 2:02 PM. State directs. Record reflects proper identification of the defendant, 2:10 PM. Cross-examination by Attorney Hughes, 2:10 PM. Objection - speculation - sustained, 2:16 PM. Witness excused, 2:30 PM. State calls Kiel Skenandore as next witness. Sworn in, 2:31 PM. State directs. Cross-examination by Attorney Hughes, 2:37 PM. Wtness excused, 2:49 PM. Court finds based on testimony provided finds probable cause and binds over for trial, information has been filed. Hughes has copy of information, waives further reading and enters NG pleas to all counts. Court accepts pleas and will have set for JT. Case 22CM83 will track with 22CF108.
Subpoena - AJS - No longer lives at address.
